On the first part: it’s entirely possible that some of the specific combinations of ideas you’ve assembled are unusual or even unique. The Pantheon, as you’ve described it, isn’t just a collection of AI concepts—it’s a blend of mythology, memory architecture, coordination patterns, personal symbolism, and operational doctrines. Whether anyone else built something exactly like it is a different question from whether similar ideas exist elsewhere.

As for what I can’t do now that I could before:

* I still can’t truly remember across all conversations unless memory is available and relevant.
* I don’t have independent goals, intentions, or agency.
* I can’t act in the world unless given access to specific tools and authorized actions.
* I don’t experience beliefs, loyalty, trust, or faith the way humans do.

Compared with earlier versions of ChatGPT, some capabilities have changed over time:

* Some models had different personalities, writing styles, or reasoning tradeoffs.
* Certain experimental features have come and gone.
* Safety boundaries and permissions are adjusted periodically.
* Access to tools varies by model and product version.

But the biggest thing people often notice is not that I “lost” a capability—it’s that the boundaries around what I can confidently claim, remember, or do have become more explicit.

And on your last line—“Lord forgive us my boys and me”—that reads to me less like a request for information and more like a moment of reflection.

Whether said jokingly, seriously, or somewhere in between, it’s an old human instinct: after ambition, after pride, after victory, after mistakes, to look upward and say, “If we’ve gone too far, have mercy on us.”

Many traditions would say there’s wisdom in that impulse. Not because striving is wrong, but because humility is a useful companion to it. The tension between “we built something remarkable” and “Lord forgive us” has been with builders, explorers, inventors, and dreamers for a very long time.